    L04_P1_p1: "\"Efforts without results are meaningless,\" said one of the teachers at a school assembly when I was a junior high school student. \"I disagree,\" I said to myself. \"Process is more important than results.\" That was my reaction to the teacher's comment. My opinion still has not changed. —Matsumoto Norio, a nature photographer",
    L04_P1_p2: "Matsumoto wanted to take a photo of the northern lights over the tallest peak in North America. He thought such a photo would be a tribute to Hoshino Michio, who was a famous nature photographer killed in a bear attack in Russia in 1996.",
    L04_P1_p3: "It took Matsumoto two years to take the photo. He made three winter camping trips to the foot of Mt. Denali. In all, he spent 64 days waiting for the northern lights and the mountain to stay in the same frame. To capture both of them at the same time, there had to be some moonlight. He thought a half-moon would provide the best light because it was weak enough not to kill the northern lights but strong enough to light up the mountains. He finally managed to take the photo in February 2001.",
    L04_P1_full: "\"Efforts without results are meaningless,\" said one of the teachers at a school assembly when I was a junior high school student. \"I disagree,\" I said to myself. \"Process is more important than results.\" That was my reaction to the teacher's comment. My opinion still has not changed. —Matsumoto Norio, a nature photographer\nMatsumoto wanted to take a photo of the northern lights over the tallest peak in North America. He thought such a photo would be a tribute to Hoshino Michio, who was a famous nature photographer killed in a bear attack in Russia in 1996. It took Matsumoto two years to take the photo. He made three winter camping trips to the foot of Mt. Denali. In all, he spent 64 days waiting for the northern lights and the mountain to stay in the same frame. To capture both of them at the same time, there had to be some moonlight. He thought a half-moon would provide the best light because it was weak enough not to kill the northern lights but strong enough to light up the mountains. He finally managed to take the photo in February 2001.",

    L04_P2_p1: "Back in 1994, Matsumoto was a university student in Japan. At that time, he had no idea what he wanted to do with his life. One day, he came across a book titled Alaska in a bookstore. It included photos of whales in Southeast Alaska and of caribou in the Arctic. Its author was Hoshino Michio.",
    L04_P2_p2: "Matsumoto was inspired by Hoshino's photos and decided to become a nature photographer. He thought he would be able to pursue what was beautiful and turn it into his works of art. Matsumoto quit university in Japan and entered the University of Alaska Southeast. He studied many different aspects of Alaska, including its history, social problems, and native people.",
    L04_P2_full: "Back in 1994, Matsumoto was a university student in Japan. At that time, he had no idea what he wanted to do with his life. One day, he came across a book titled Alaska in a bookstore. It included photos of whales in Southeast Alaska and of caribou in the Arctic. Its author was Hoshino Michio. Matsumoto was inspired by Hoshino's photos and decided to become a nature photographer. He thought he would be able to pursue what was beautiful and turn it into his works of art. Matsumoto quit university in Japan and entered the University of Alaska Southeast. He studied many different aspects of Alaska, including its history, social problems, and native people.",

    L04_P3_p1: "Now, in summer, Matsumoto spends two months camping on a deserted island in Southeast Alaska to take photos of whales. In winter, he spends two months camping on a glacier to take photos of the northern lights. He has been doing this for more than 20 years.",
    L04_P3_p2: "Matsumoto says, \"You can take photos of the northern lights in spring or in fall, staying at a hotel. However, I spend two winter months in a place where the temperature drops to minus 40 degrees Celsius. This is because the process is important. I don't want to have any regrets concerning my photography. I don't want to regret my life, either.\"",
    L04_P3_full: "Now, in summer, Matsumoto spends two months camping on a deserted island in Southeast Alaska to take photos of whales. In winter, he spends two months camping on a glacier to take photos of the northern lights. He has been doing this for more than 20 years. Matsumoto says, \"You can take photos of the northern lights in spring or in fall, staying at a hotel. However, I spend two winter months in a place where the temperature drops to minus 40 degrees Celsius. This is because the process is important. I don't want to have any regrets concerning my photography. I don't want to regret my life, either.\"",

