    L06_P1_p1: "In many parts of the world, people celebrate Halloween on October 31. They carve pumpkins into lanterns, dress up in crazy outfits, and go trick-or-treating.",
    L06_P1_p2: "Here in Japan too, Halloween has become a big event in recent years. When autumn comes, shops and stores offer a wide selection of Halloween goods. Many of us enjoy Halloween at home with our family or have fun by participating in or watching street parties. The market size of Halloween is as large as that of Valentine's Day, only topped by Christmas.",
    L06_P1_p3: "However, it seems that we don't know or care about the real meaning of Halloween. There's more to Halloween than just pumpkins, costumes, and parties. Let's look at its origin and history.",
    L06_P1_full: "In many parts of the world, people celebrate Halloween on October 31. They carve pumpkins into lanterns, dress up in crazy outfits, and go trick-or-treating. Here in Japan too, Halloween has become a big event in recent years. When autumn comes, shops and stores offer a wide selection of Halloween goods. Many of us enjoy Halloween at home with our family or have fun by participating in or watching street parties. The market size of Halloween is as large as that of Valentine's Day, only topped by Christmas. However, it seems that we don't know or care about the real meaning of Halloween. There's more to Halloween than just pumpkins, costumes, and parties. Let's look at its origin and history.",

    L06_P2_p4: "It is widely believed that current Halloween practices originated from an ancient Celtic festival. This festival dates back to over 2,000 years ago. It was held every October 31 to mark both the end of the harvest season and the beginning of winter.",
    L06_P2_p5: "The Celts believed that during this festival time, the boundary between this world and the otherworld could be easily crossed, and that evil spirits from the otherworld walked around the streets and villages at night. To calm and quiet them, the Celts left sweet treats outside. This custom, it is said, changed into trick-or-treating.",
    L06_P2_full: "It is widely believed that current Halloween practices originated from an ancient Celtic festival. This festival dates back to over 2,000 years ago. It was held every October 31 to mark both the end of the harvest season and the beginning of winter. The Celts believed that during this festival time, the boundary between this world and the otherworld could be easily crossed, and that evil spirits from the otherworld walked around the streets and villages at night. To calm and quiet them, the Celts left sweet treats outside. This custom, it is said, changed into trick-or-treating.",

    L06_P3_p6: "Also, the Celts disguised themselves with costumes and masks. They believed that evil spirits would mistake them for fellow evil spirits and not harm them. Obviously, dressing up in scary costumes for Halloween comes from this Celtic custom.",
    L06_P3_p7: "Moreover, the Celts carved turnips into lanterns and displayed them with a candle inside to scare away evil spirits. Over time, these lanterns have come to be used for decorative purposes on Halloween, with turnips often replaced by pumpkins.",
    L06_P3_full: "Also, the Celts disguised themselves with costumes and masks. They believed that evil spirits would mistake them for fellow evil spirits and not harm them. Obviously, dressing up in scary costumes for Halloween comes from this Celtic custom. Moreover, the Celts carved turnips into lanterns and displayed them with a candle inside to scare away evil spirits. Over time, these lanterns have come to be used for decorative purposes on Halloween, with turnips often replaced by pumpkins.",

    L06_P4_p8: "Now, when and how did these Celtic customs spread around the world? The answer is twofold. First, Irish immigrants, descendants of the Celts, brought many of their customs to America. After the mid-19th century, some of them became popular there, eventually resulting in current Halloween practices. Second, as American popular culture reached more and more countries, Halloween practices in America also spread to Australia, Germany, Japan, and interestingly to the U.K. in the last century.",
    L06_P4_p9: "For most of us, Halloween now holds little or no religious significance. But we should remember that some religious people do not accept it because of its origin and association with evil spirits.",
    L06_P4_full: "Now, when and how did these Celtic customs spread around the world? The answer is twofold. First, Irish immigrants, descendants of the Celts, brought many of their customs to America. After the mid-19th century, some of them became popular there, eventually resulting in current Halloween practices. Second, as American popular culture reached more and more countries, Halloween practices in America also spread to Australia, Germany, Japan, and interestingly to the U.K. in the last century. For most of us, Halloween now holds little or no religious significance. But we should remember that some religious people do not accept it because of its origin and association with evil spirits.",

    // ==========================================
